"Ackerman A.S., Kirkpatrick M.P., Stevens D.E., Toon O.B.","The impact of humidity above stratiform clouds on indirect aerosol climate forcing",2004,"Nature","432","7020",,"1014","1017",,,10.1038/nature03174,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-11144232674&partnerID=40&md5=e7054cb1dc96a580917ca83f4f178968","NASA Ames Research Center, Moffett Field, CA 94035, United States; University of Tasmania, Hobart, Tasmania 7001, Australia; Lawrence Livermore Natl. Laboratory, Livermore, CA 94552, United States; University of Colorado, Boulder, CO 80309, United States","Ackerman, A.S., NASA Ames Research Center, Moffett Field, CA 94035, United States; Kirkpatrick, M.P., University of Tasmania, Hobart, Tasmania 7001, Australia; Stevens, D.E., Lawrence Livermore Natl. Laboratory, Livermore, CA 94552, United States; Toon, O.B., University of Colorado, Boulder, CO 80309, United States","Some of the global warming from anthropogenic greenhouse gases is offset by increased reflection of solar radiation by clouds with smaller droplets that form in air polluted with aerosol particles that serve as cloud condensation nuclei. The resulting cooling tendency, termed the indirect aerosol forcing, is thought to be comparable in magnitude to the forcing by anthropogenic CO 2, but it is difficult to estimate because the physical processes that determine global aerosol and cloud populations are pooriy understood. Smaller cloud droplets not only reflect sunlight more effectively, but also inhibit precipitation, which is expected to result in increased cloud water. Such an increase in cloud water would result in even more reflective clouds, further increasing the indirect forcing. Marine boundary-layer clouds polluted by aerosol particles, however, are not generally observed to hold more water. Here we simulate stratocumulus clouds with a fluid dynamics model that includes detailed treatments of cloud microphysics and radiative transfer. Our simulations show that the response of cloud water to suppression of precipitation from increased droplet concentrations is determined by a competition between moistening from decreased surface precipitation and drying from increased entrainment of overlying air. Only when the overlying air is humid or droplet concentrations are very low does sufficient precipitation reach the surface to allow cloud water to increase with droplet concentrations. Otherwise, the response of cloud water to aerosol-induced suppression of precipitation is dominated by enhanced entrainment of overlying dry air. In this scenario, cloud water is reduced as droplet concentrations increase, which diminishes the indirect climate forcing.",,"Climate forcing; Cloud condensation nuclei; Greenhouse gases; Stratiform clouds; Air pollution; Atmospheric aerosols; Boundary layers; Climate change; Clouds; Condensation; Global warming; Greenhouse effect; Precipitation (chemical); Supercooling; Atmospheric humidity; aerosol; climate forcing; global warming; humidity; stratiform cloud; aerosol; article; climate; cloud; greenhouse effect; humidity; meteorology; particle size; precipitation; priority journal; simulation; solar radiation; surface property",,,,,,"Twomey, S., Pollution and the planetary albedo (1974) Atmos. Environ., 8, pp. 1251-1256; Houghton, J.T., (2001) Climate Change 2001: The Scientific Basis. Contribution of Working Group I to the Third Assessment Report of the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change, , Ch. 5 and 6 (Cambridge Univ. Press, UK/USA); Albrecht, B., Aerosols, cloud microphysics, and fractional cloudiness (1989) Science, 245, pp. 1227-1230; Pincus, R., Baker, M.B., Effect of precipitation on the albedo susceptibility of clouds in the marine boundary layer (1994) Nature, 372, pp. 250-252; Ackerman, A.S., Effects of aerosols on cloud albedo: Evaluation of Twomey's parameterization of cloud susceptibility using measurements of ship tracks (2000) J. Atmos. Sci., 57, pp. 2684-2695; Platnick, S., The role of background cloud microphysics in the radiative formation of ship tracks (2000) J. Atmos. Sci., 57, pp. 2607-2624; Coakley Jr., J.A., Walsh, C.D., Limits to the aerosol indirect radiative effect derived from observations of ship tracks (2002) J. Atmos. Sci., 59, pp. 668-680; Brenguier, J.L., Radiative properties of boundary layer clouds: Droplet effective radius versus number concentration (2000) J. Atmos. Sci., 57, pp. 803-821; Radke, L.F., Coakley Jr., J.A.J., King, M.D., Direct and remote sensing observations of the effects of ships on clouds (1989) Science, 246, pp. 1146-1149; Duynkerke, P.G., Zhang, H., Jonker, P.J., Microphysical and turbulent structure of nocturnal stratocumulus as observed during ASTEX (1995) J. Atmos. Sci., 52, pp. 2763-2777; Bretherton, C.S., Austin, P., Siems, S.T., Cloudiness and marine boundary layer dynamics in the ASTEX Lagrangian experiments: Part II: Cloudiness, drizzle, surface fluxes, and entrainment (1995) J. Atmos. Sci., 52, pp. 2724-2735; Stevens, B., On entrainment rates in nocturnal marine stratocumulus (2003) Q. J.R. Meteorol. Soc., 129, pp. 3469-3493; Stevens, B., Dynamics and chemistry of marine stratocumulus - DYCOMS-II (2003) Bull. Am. Meteorol. Soc., 84, pp. 579-593; Stevens, B., Cotton, W.R., Feingold, G., Moeng, C.-H., Large-eddy simulations of strongly precipitating, shallow, stratocumulus-topped boundary layers (1998) J. Atmos. Sci., 55, pp. 3616-3638; Randall, D.A., Conditional instability of the first kind upside-down (1980) J. Atmos. Sci., 37, pp. 125-130; Deardorff, J.W., Cloud top entrainment instability (1980) J. Atmos. Sci., 37, pp. 131-147; MacVean, M.K., Mason, P.J., Cloud-top entrainment instability through small-scale mixing and its parameterization in numerical models (1990) J. Atmos. Sci., 47, pp. 1012-1030; Ackerman, A.S., Toon, O.B., Stevens, D.E., Coakley Jr., J.A., Enhancement of cloud cover and suppression of noctural drizzle in stratocumulus polluted by haze (2003) Geophys. Res. Lett., 30. , doi:10.1029/2002